Core JavaScript (Beginner to Intermediate)

These check your foundation ‚Äî syntax, basics, and core behavior.

‚úÖ Basics & Syntax

~ What are the different data types in JavaScript?

<!-- In Js there are two types of data types
    1) Premitive data types: premitive are imuttable and are stored by value
        7 types of premitive data types: string, bigInt, number, boolean, null, undefined, sybmbol
    2) Non-premitive data types: non-premitive are mutable and are stored by reference
     ex: Object, array and function
     -->

~ Difference between var, let, and const.

<!-- we can differenciate var let and const by many types:
1) declaration: var can be re-declared and updated in the same scope.
& let and const cannot be re-declared in the same scope.

2) Initialization: var and let can be declare without assigning an initial value,
const must be initialize at the time of declaration.

3) scope: var is functional scope,
let and const are block scope;

4) hoisting: all three ae hosited but they behave differently
var is hoisted with and initialize with undefined,
let and const are hoisted but remain in the TDZ. until their declaration line
 -->

~ What is hoisting? Give examples.

<!-- Hoisting is a javascript mechanism where all the function and variable declaration are moved to the top of their scope during the compilation phase, before the code is executed.
Variables declared with var are hoisted and initialized as undefined, while let and const are hoisted but remain in the Temporal Dead Zone.
Function declarations are fully hoisted, allowing them to be called before definition
 -->

~ What are template literals?

<!-- Template literals, introduced in ES6, provide a cleaner and more powerful way to handle strings using backticks. They support string interpolation (${}), multi-line strings, and expression embedding, replacing complex string concatenation and improving readability.
 -->

~ Explain the difference between == and ===.

<!--
The == operator checks equality after performing type coercion, meaning it converts operands to the same type before comparison.
The === operator, known as strict equality, checks both type and value, making it more predictable and recommended for most comparisons in modern JavaScript.
 -->

~ What are truthy and falsy values in JS?

<!--These are the only values considered falsy:
false
0
-0
"" (empty string)
null
undefined
NaN

Any value not listed above is truthy, including:

Non-empty strings ‚Üí "Mahi"

Non-zero numbers ‚Üí 42, -7

Objects and arrays ‚Üí {}, []

Functions ‚Üí function() {}
 -->

