What is debouncing and throttling?
<!-- 
Debouncing are throttling both are used to optimatization of an app but they both worked differnetly
we use debouncing to get result after the certain time period when action are being stopped.
and on other hand we use throttling 
 -->

What is the difference between innerHTML, innerText, and textContent?

<!--
innerHTML, innerText, and textContent are used to get or set the content of a DOM element, but they work differently:

innerHTML returns or sets the HTML markup inside an element. It parses HTML tags, so it can add or remove elements dynamically.
Example: div.innerHTML = "<b>Hello</b>" renders bold text.

innerText returns only the visible text of an element as displayed on the page, respecting CSS styles like display: none or visibility: hidden.
Example: It ignores hidden elements.

textContent returns the raw text of an element and its children, ignoring any HTML tags and CSS styles. It‚Äôs faster and safer for inserting plain text because it doesn‚Äôt parse HTML.
 -->

How do you dynamically create and append elements in the DOM?

<!--We can dynamically create elements in the DOM using document.createElement() and then insert them using methods like appendChild() or append().
Before appending, we can modify the element‚Äôs content, attributes, and styles.
appendChild() adds a single node, while append() can add multiple nodes
 -->

What is localStorage, sessionStorage, and cookies?

<!--
localStorage and sessionStorage are part of the Web Storage API used for storing key‚Äìvalue pairs in the browser, while cookies are used mainly for server‚Äìclient communication.
localStorage persists even after the browser closes, sessionStorage lasts only for a tab session, and cookies can have a custom expiry date and are automatically sent with HTTP requests
 -->

Difference between DOMContentLoaded and load events?

<!--
DOMContentLoaded fires when the HTML document is completely parsed and the DOM is ready, without waiting for external resources.
load fires only after the entire page ‚Äî including all assets ‚Äî has fully loaded.
Use DOMContentLoaded for initializing scripts that manipulate the DOM early, and load for tasks that require all resources to be available.
 -->

What is the Shadow DOM?

<!--
The Shadow DOM is a browser feature that lets you create encapsulated DOM trees with their own scoped styles and markup. It prevents style and behavior conflicts across components, enabling better modularity and reusability in web applications.
 -->

